profile_positions.description:
Primary responsible for the implementation of genome editing tools in the Department, to facilitate comparative genetic studies in diverse plant species, with main tasks covering:

 	- Generation and Optimization of Novel CRISPR/Cas9 Constructs: conceptualizing and designing a modular system toolbox for genome editing and transcriptional regulation via dCas9-based transcription factors; 
 	- Establishment of Protocols for CRISPR/Cas9: responsible to fine-tune cloning methods, mutant screening and identification, as well as to teach and assist colleagues in the methodology;
 	- CRISPR/Cas9 mutants: generating targeted gene modified mutants in different plant species, such as tomato, Arabidopsis, Capsella and Cardamine;
 	- Cardamine Transformation: analysis of different binary vectors, to identify ideal backbone to improve plant transformation yield; 
 	- Tilling Population Analysis: screening of new alleles for different genes in Cardamine hirsuta through Illumina sequencing coupled to a multidimensional pooling strategy.

Performed diverse research functions in the Sustainable Liquid Biofuels from Biomass Biorefining (SUNLIBB), a four-year consortium including 13 European research institutions and the Center of Biological and Industrial Process for Biofuels (CeProBIO), a sister consortium in Brazil:

 	- Biobased Economic Group: postdoctoral researcher of the SUNLIBB consortium, performing numerous administrative functions such as developing presentations on work progress, writing reports, and participating in phone meetings;
 	- Miscanthus Samples Handling and Distribution: collaboration with various partners in SUNLIBB and CeProBIO for the collection and preparation of numerous Miscanthus genotypes samples; 
 	- Mapping Population Analysis: coordination of technicians to initiate biochemical analyses on Miscanthus sinensis mapping population (BIOMIS) while analysing SUNLIBB mapping population to map quantitative trait loci (QTLs) related to biomass composition and saccharification potential variation through genotyping by sequence (GBS) based on DNA fragment sequence;
 	- Bioinformatics and Gene Expression Analysis: identification and characterization of key genes involved in the Miscanthus secondary cell wall biosynthesis through development of degenerated primers and collaboration with the Genetics Department to establish a user-friendly de novo transcriptome browser; 
 	- Miscanthus Transformation Protocol: application of various strategies, including agrobacterium mediated transformation, and initiation of testing of 60 Miscanthus genotypes to improve the transformation process.

Demonstrated knowledge on plant adaptation to salinity by characterizing the evolution and function of the SOS1 gene in Arabidopsis and Thellungiella and by exploiting natural variation in Arabidopsis to identify alleles underlying salt tolerance.

Facilitated and implemented training to colleagues in various techniques:

 	- Yeast Work: expertise in yeast one-hybrid and yeast two-hybrid screenings; and communication with researchers in Switzerland and the United States to obtain Gateway vectors and yeast strain to conduct experiments;
 	-Gateway Cloning Technology: implementation and facilitation of training on simple and multisite Gateway;
 	- Subcellular Localization: responsibility in guiding and educating colleagues in transient expression analysis in tobacco by leaf infiltration assay.

Efficiently conducted the characterization of three SIAMESE-related genes through various experiments:

 	- Y1H: identification of possible transcription factor binding to the SMR genes promoter region 
 	- Y2H and BIFC: testing of the direct interaction in vitro and in vivo between SMR proteins with CDKs
 	- Overexpression Analysis: overexpression of individual SMR genes to determine the phenotype of mutant plants, as well as to analyse if the changes align with projected functions
 	- Knockout Analysis: analysis of phenotypes for available SALK mutant lines, and construction of silencing lines largely mitigating the gene expression;
 	- Spatial Control of Gene Expression: generation of transgenic Arabidopsis plants possessing the promoter region of SMR genes fused to the GUS reporter gene;
 	- Subcellular Localization Analysis: identification of the subcellular localization of the SMR proteins by fuse full-length open reading frames to the enhanced GFP reporter protein (EGFP), followed by the insertion of constructs in Arabidopsis;
 	- Phenotypic Analysis of Plants Under Genotoxic Stress: analysis of plants grown under different genotoxins, including MMC, MMS, bleomycin, hydroxyurea, UV-B and cisplatin.
